    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "subtitle": "The Most Important Concept in Time & Work",
          "tags": [
            "High Weightage",
            "Shortcuts",
            "JKSSB"
          ],
          "title": "Work and Efficiency",
          "type": "hero"
        },
        {
          "content": "Efficiency is the amount of work completed in a unit of time. A more efficient worker completes more work in the same time or the same work in less time.",
          "highlight": true,
          "icon": "⚡",
          "title": "What is Efficiency?",
          "type": "fact_card"
        },
        {
          "description": "Efficiency and time are inversely proportional for the same work.",
          "formula": "Efficiency ∝ 1 / Time",
          "title": "Efficiency Relationship",
          "type": "formula"
        },
        {
          "content": "If A is twice as efficient as B, then A will take half the time taken by B to complete the same work.",
          "icon": "📌",
          "title": "Golden Rule",
          "type": "fact_card"
        },
        {
          "left_header": "Efficiency Ratio",
          "right_header": "Time Ratio",
          "rows": [
            {
              "left": "1 : 2",
              "right": "2 : 1"
            },
            {
              "left": "2 : 3",
              "right": "3 : 2"
            },
            {
              "left": "3 : 5",
              "right": "5 : 3"
            },
            {
              "left": "4 : 7",
              "right": "7 : 4"
            },
            {
              "left": "5 : 8",
              "right": "8 : 5"
            }
          ],
          "title": "Efficiency vs Time",
          "type": "comparison"
        },
        {
          "steps": [
            "Find efficiency ratio",
            "Reverse it to get time ratio",
            "Assume total work using LCM",
            "Calculate work per day",
            "Find required time"
          ],
          "title": "How Efficiency Questions Are Solved",
          "type": "process_flow"
        },
        {
          "content": "In competitive exams, total work is often assumed as the LCM of individual completion times. This eliminates fractions and makes calculations faster.",
          "icon": "🎯",
          "title": "Why LCM Method Works",
          "type": "fact_card"
        },
        {
          "headers": [
            "Completion Time",
            "Assumed Total Work",
            "One Day Work"
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              "10 days",
              "30 units",
              "3 units"
            ],
            [
              "15 days",
              "30 units",
              "2 units"
            ],
            [
              "20 days",
              "60 units",
              "3 units"
            ],
            [
              "30 days",
              "60 units",
              "2 units"
            ]
          ],
          "title": "LCM Shortcut Table",
          "type": "table"
        },
        {
          "answer": "12 days",
          "find": "Time taken by A",
          "formula_used": "Efficiency Ratio = Inverse of Time Ratio",
          "given": [
            "A is twice as efficient as B",
            "B completes a work in 24 days"
          ],
          "steps": [
            "Efficiency ratio A:B = 2:1",
            "Time ratio A:B = 1:2",
            "If B takes 24 days",
            "A takes 24 × (1/2)",
            "A takes 12 days"
          ],
          "title": "Efficiency Example",
          "type": "solved_example"
        },
        {
          "answer": "7.2 days",
          "find": "Time taken together",
          "formula_used": "Time = Total Work / Combined Daily Work",
          "given": [
            "A completes work in 12 days",
            "B completes work in 18 days"
          ],
          "steps": [
            "LCM(12,18) = 36",
            "Assume total work = 36 units",
            "A's one day work = 36/12 = 3 units",
            "B's one day work = 36/18 = 2 units",
            "Together = 5 units/day",
            "Time = 36/5 days"
          ],
          "title": "LCM Method Example",
          "type": "solved_example"
        },
        {
          "correct": "Time ratio is always the inverse of efficiency ratio.",
          "tip": "Higher efficiency means less time.",
          "title": "Most Common Trap",
          "type": "exam_trap",
          "wrong": "Using efficiency ratio directly as time ratio."
        },
        {
          "memory_trick": "Efficiency Increases → Time decreases.",
          "mnemonic": "EIT",
          "title": "Memory Trick",
          "type": "mnemonic"
        },
        {
          "content": "Whenever completion times are given, first check if the LCM method can simplify the question. It is usually faster than fractions.",
          "title": "Exam Shortcut",
          "type": "note_card",
          "variant": "remember"
